WEBVTT

00:01.830 --> 00:05.330
Dre: My son. My namesake.

00:05.330 --> 00:08.330
My God, he bums me out.

00:08.330 --> 00:11.580
Junior had decided to take
a gap year for himself,

00:11.580 --> 00:13.830
and I had agreed to respect
his choice.

00:13.830 --> 00:18.500
[ Sour guitar chords play ]

00:18.500 --> 00:22.040
The problem was, he wasn't
giving me much to respect.

00:22.040 --> 00:24.120
Welcome back
to the podcast.

00:24.120 --> 00:27.120
Today's guest, Jack,
has canceled.

00:27.120 --> 00:28.120
That's it!

00:28.120 --> 00:30.790
I'm taking you to work!

00:30.790 --> 00:32.380
And get rid
of that damn rabbit!

00:38.920 --> 00:41.250
Ready for my first day
at Dad's office!

00:41.250 --> 00:44.120
Aah, look at you going
to work!

00:44.120 --> 00:45.620
-Mm-hmm.
-Mm-hmm.

00:45.620 --> 00:47.540
Finally ready to do something
with that gap year.

00:47.540 --> 00:48.710
Aw, come on.

00:48.710 --> 00:50.290
Hey, I've done things,
okay?

00:50.290 --> 00:52.420
My podcast
has two subscribers.

00:52.420 --> 00:53.960
Only one.
I'm sorry, sweetheart.

00:53.960 --> 00:55.080
I-I unsubscribed.

00:55.080 --> 00:57.620
All right.
Come on. Let's go, son.

00:57.620 --> 01:00.080
You can see a strong, black man
handle his business.

01:00.080 --> 01:01.880
I didn't realize you worked
with Terry Crews.

01:01.880 --> 01:03.420
[ Junior and Rainbow laugh ]

01:03.420 --> 01:04.750
That was good, sweetie!

01:04.750 --> 01:05.750
I'm just messing with you,
big guy.
No, it wasn't.

01:05.750 --> 01:06.790
-It was good.
-I'll be in the car.

01:06.790 --> 01:08.250
Yeah. Okay.
[ Cellphone chimes ]

01:08.250 --> 01:09.290
He's killing me, Bow.

01:09.290 --> 01:10.670
Hmm.

01:10.670 --> 01:11.620
[ Gasps ]

01:11.620 --> 01:13.790
Oh, no.
What?

01:13.790 --> 01:15.920
Erica just quit.

01:15.920 --> 01:17.080
Who?

01:17.080 --> 01:18.460
Black Nanny Two, Dre.

01:18.460 --> 01:19.750
This couldn't come
at a worse time.

01:19.750 --> 01:21.460
I have four surgeries
today.

01:21.460 --> 01:23.080
How are we gonna
find somebody?

01:23.080 --> 01:24.620
Hey, don't worry about it,
baby.

01:24.620 --> 01:25.790
I'll make some calls.

01:25.790 --> 01:27.120
Thank you.
Mm-hmm.

01:27.120 --> 01:28.580
Mama?!
Ruby: Yeah?

01:28.580 --> 01:30.120
You want to be
Devante's nanny?
Okay.

01:30.120 --> 01:32.960
If my baby needs a nanny
for his baby, I'll do it.

01:32.960 --> 01:34.920
That's great.
That's great.

01:34.920 --> 01:36.330
Come on, now.
I'm serious.

01:36.330 --> 01:37.750
I'll nanny that baby.

01:37.750 --> 01:38.750
-See?
-Really, Ruby?

01:38.750 --> 01:40.580
Mm-hmm.
Huh.

01:40.580 --> 01:42.580
Are you bonded?
Uh, no.

01:42.580 --> 01:44.960
Do you have
your class C driver's license?

01:44.960 --> 01:45.960
Suspended.

01:45.960 --> 01:47.170
CPR certificate?

01:47.170 --> 01:48.620
Well, she has been known
to choke people.

01:48.620 --> 01:51.000
What are
your qualifications?

01:51.000 --> 01:53.290
Andre, did you die
when you were a baby?

01:53.290 --> 01:54.330
Not that I know of.

01:54.330 --> 01:55.460
Qualified.

01:55.460 --> 01:56.460
Mm-hmm.
Come on now.

01:56.460 --> 01:58.040
I love that little man.

01:58.040 --> 01:59.790
Yeah.
Come on, baby.

01:59.790 --> 02:02.380
[ Chuckles ]
How could you say no
to that?

02:02.380 --> 02:04.790
Very easily.
No!

02:04.790 --> 02:06.120
What?

02:06.120 --> 02:10.290
But I am desperate,
so...

02:10.290 --> 02:11.670
yes, we can try it.

02:11.670 --> 02:13.790
That's fine.
Oh, that's wonderful.

02:13.790 --> 02:14.790
That's good.

02:14.790 --> 02:15.790
Mm-hmm.

02:15.790 --> 02:17.880
I'm gonna need three weeks off
at Christmas.

02:17.880 --> 02:18.880
Yeah?

02:18.880 --> 02:21.000
Hey, hey.
You know where I go.

02:22.460 --> 02:23.960
[ Indistinct conversation,
laughter ]

02:23.960 --> 02:25.170
Stevens:
What's wrong, Dre?

02:25.170 --> 02:28.330
Oh. Did you accidentally
wipe some Hot Cheetos dust

02:28.330 --> 02:29.670
on your fancy sweater?

02:29.670 --> 02:31.500
No.
You know, Junior's gonna be

02:31.500 --> 02:32.880
interning here
a few days a week,

02:32.880 --> 02:35.330
and I'm trying to teach him
some responsibility,

02:35.330 --> 02:38.000
but I'm worried
he's a lost cause.

02:38.000 --> 02:40.000
-Hmm.
-Well...

02:40.000 --> 02:41.330
Hey, guys.

02:41.330 --> 02:43.040
Thanks
for the opportunity.

02:43.040 --> 02:44.330
-Just interning?
-Mm-hmm.

02:44.330 --> 02:45.670
That's good to know.

02:45.670 --> 02:47.170
I thought he was here
to take my place

02:47.170 --> 02:49.000
as your wingman
and confidant.

02:49.000 --> 02:50.170
[ Chuckles ]

02:50.170 --> 02:51.380
Or to take my job.

02:52.540 --> 02:54.000
[ Whispering ] Is that
what you're here to do?

02:54.000 --> 02:55.080
[ Louder ] Is it?

02:55.080 --> 02:57.330
'Cause if it is,
you got to tell me.

02:57.330 --> 02:59.670
You also got to tell me
where you got that sweater

02:59.670 --> 03:01.000
because it's fire.

03:01.000 --> 03:03.000
[ Chuckles nervously ]
My -- My mom bought it for me.

03:03.000 --> 03:04.420
Your mom's fire, too.

03:04.420 --> 03:07.880
Well, young man, you have chosen
a great time to be here

03:07.880 --> 03:10.040
because your dad just hit it
out of the park

03:10.040 --> 03:11.710
with the Google campaign.

03:11.710 --> 03:13.250
-Yes! Grr!
-Ah, yeah.

03:13.250 --> 03:16.540
You hear that? They put
some respect on your dad's name.

03:16.540 --> 03:18.620
And we're going to need
another home run

03:18.620 --> 03:21.210
with our new client,
Hometown Market.

03:21.210 --> 03:22.420
They -- They're --
They're trying to take

03:22.420 --> 03:24.290
their comfort food
from the suburbs

03:24.290 --> 03:25.460
to the urban space.

03:25.460 --> 03:26.380
So black people.

03:26.380 --> 03:28.460
Uh, or gentrifying
whites.

03:28.460 --> 03:30.790
Connor's right.
It's -- It's the blacks.

03:30.790 --> 03:32.710
And, uh, some Hispanics.

03:32.710 --> 03:34.580
You know,
people who ride the bus.

03:34.580 --> 03:37.040
[ Sighs ]
Okay, guys.

03:37.040 --> 03:38.210
We're getting off track,
all right?

03:38.210 --> 03:41.960
Maybe we should look
at this Hometown Market Menu.

03:41.960 --> 03:43.750
Maybe that will give us
some ideas.

03:43.750 --> 03:45.040
These names
are kind of bland.

03:45.040 --> 03:46.120
"Tuna melt"?

03:46.120 --> 03:47.710
"Turkey pot pie"?

03:47.710 --> 03:50.290
Maybe we can give these dishes
new urban names.

03:50.290 --> 03:51.920
Ah.
Like Charlie.

03:51.920 --> 03:54.750
[ Chuckles ]
Charlie's an urban name.

03:54.750 --> 03:57.120
Ooh, these Charlies
look delicious.

03:57.120 --> 03:59.080
Don't put no hot sauce
on my Charlies.

03:59.080 --> 04:00.830
Why don't we name them
after something

04:00.830 --> 04:03.920
that black people like,
like rappers?

04:03.920 --> 04:07.000
Okay, we like a lot more
than just rappers.

04:07.000 --> 04:09.000
Yeah, of course you do.
But how about this?

04:09.000 --> 04:12.460
The Run DM Seafood Tower.

04:12.460 --> 04:15.120
Or -- Or the Kanye Western
Omelet.

04:15.120 --> 04:16.120
-Ooh, I got one.
-Nice.

04:16.120 --> 04:17.960
The Notorious BLT.

04:17.960 --> 04:19.580
[ Laughter ]

04:19.580 --> 04:22.080
Sorry, the --
the Cardi BLT.

04:22.080 --> 04:24.290
Oh, oh, oh!
I got a good slogan.

04:24.290 --> 04:27.500
"Hometown Market:
get in here, Boo."

04:27.500 --> 04:29.620
Why don't we just move on
for now, okay?

04:29.620 --> 04:31.960
And, you know, I'll look
at all these things

04:31.960 --> 04:33.960
on my own
a little later.

04:33.960 --> 04:36.290
That is why
you are a star, Dre.

04:36.290 --> 04:37.290
All right.

04:37.290 --> 04:39.290
Well, I'm gonna go play
some golf.

04:39.290 --> 04:40.830
Oh, very good.
Very good.

04:40.830 --> 04:42.120
Hey.
Hey.

04:42.120 --> 04:44.460
Mommy's home just in time
for snack.

04:44.460 --> 04:46.120
What's it gonna be,
huh?

04:46.120 --> 04:47.040
Avocado?

04:47.040 --> 04:48.290
I think
he's still full.

04:48.290 --> 04:50.290
He had a cupcake
at the park.

04:50.290 --> 04:51.960
You bought him
a cupcake?

04:51.960 --> 04:56.120
No. A handsome man
enjoying cupcakes on a bench

04:56.120 --> 04:57.290
gave us one.

04:57.290 --> 04:59.790
Ha, he gave 'em
to all the children.

04:59.790 --> 05:02.960
A stranger was handing out
cupcakes at a park,

05:02.960 --> 05:04.290
and he gave one
to my baby?

05:04.290 --> 05:05.670
You forgot "handsome."

05:05.670 --> 05:06.960
[ Laughs ]

05:06.960 --> 05:09.120
I don't take cupcakes
from uggos.

05:09.120 --> 05:11.540
I wasn't worried
about his hotness.

05:11.540 --> 05:12.620
Ruby?

05:12.620 --> 05:13.830
Hmm?

05:13.830 --> 05:16.170
You need to read
Devante's bible

05:16.170 --> 05:19.170
and get familiar
with the rules.
Mm-hmm.

05:19.170 --> 05:22.170
First off, don't take things
from strangers.

05:22.170 --> 05:23.670
And other headlines --

05:23.670 --> 05:25.170
no screens

05:25.170 --> 05:28.580
and no choking hazards
like hot dogs and grapes.

05:28.580 --> 05:29.500
Or --
Oh, come on, Rainbow.

05:29.500 --> 05:31.000
Babies love grapes.

05:31.000 --> 05:34.500
I used to tie a bag of grapes
around Dre's neck

05:34.500 --> 05:36.330
so he could snack and play.

05:36.330 --> 05:38.420
So he could choke
hands-free.

05:38.420 --> 05:40.210
[ Chuckles ]
Okay.

05:40.210 --> 05:42.880
[ Singsong voice ]
Let's go with Mommy.

05:42.880 --> 05:44.540
[ Grunts ]

05:44.540 --> 05:45.670
[ Normal voice ]
Read my bible.

05:45.670 --> 05:48.000
I'll read your bible right away,
Rainbow.

05:48.000 --> 05:50.330
Thank you.
See you later, Devante.

05:50.330 --> 05:52.500
See you later,
reckless grandma.

05:52.500 --> 05:54.420
Bye.

05:54.420 --> 05:56.580
Diane: What are you doing
in my room?

05:56.580 --> 05:59.460
And give me one good reason
not to snap your neck right now.

05:59.460 --> 06:00.460
You know what?
Don't.

06:00.460 --> 06:01.920
I'm in the mood
to snap necks.

06:01.920 --> 06:04.210
I'm trying to crack
the parental-control code

06:04.210 --> 06:05.540
on this TV

06:05.540 --> 06:07.380
so I can watch
the horror movie "Unfriended."

06:07.380 --> 06:08.790
You can't crack that code.

06:08.790 --> 06:10.210
You're not good
at numbers.

06:10.210 --> 06:11.710
Keep doubting me.
You'll see.

06:11.710 --> 06:13.040
Come on.
Move.

06:13.040 --> 06:14.960
0-0-0-8.

06:14.960 --> 06:16.250
[ Beeps ]
Dang it.

06:16.250 --> 06:18.920
0-0-0-9.

06:18.920 --> 06:20.460
[ Beeps ]
Dang it.

06:20.460 --> 06:22.460
0-0-0-10.

06:22.460 --> 06:24.750
[ Beeps ]
It -- It won't fit.

06:24.750 --> 06:27.920
How are we
in the same grade?
[ Beeps ]

06:27.920 --> 06:29.710
Good first day,
huh?

06:29.710 --> 06:31.790
Got to see your old man
in action,

06:31.790 --> 06:33.420
handling business.

06:33.420 --> 06:34.880
Yeah.

06:34.880 --> 06:36.920
Do your co-workers always talk
like that?

06:36.920 --> 06:39.080
Hmm?
Their ideas
were pretty offensive.

06:39.080 --> 06:41.460
It's a creative business, son,
you know.

06:41.460 --> 06:43.460
People need to get
their juices flowing,

06:43.460 --> 06:46.580
but I keep a check
on their worst instincts

06:46.580 --> 06:48.080
to make sure
none of that bad stuff

06:48.080 --> 06:48.960
gets in the work.

06:48.960 --> 06:50.120
Hmm.

06:50.120 --> 06:51.920
Seems like they said
a bunch of racist things,

06:51.920 --> 06:53.500
and you just let it slide.

06:53.500 --> 06:56.170
Hey! Hey, hey, son.

06:56.170 --> 06:58.170
I don't let anything slide,
all right?

06:58.170 --> 07:01.000
They know when I sigh,
they better tighten up.

07:01.000 --> 07:02.330
Oh, yeah.

07:02.330 --> 07:05.790
I hear loud sighing
is what ended slavery!

07:05.790 --> 07:08.120
And we all remember
the sigh on Washington.

07:08.120 --> 07:11.120
Okay, what the [bleep]
Huh?

07:11.120 --> 07:13.080
If you weren't so busy
judging me,

07:13.080 --> 07:14.790
you would have noticed
that I was the one

07:14.790 --> 07:16.620
steering the conversation
in there

07:16.620 --> 07:18.620
to make sure that we had
the best product

07:18.620 --> 07:20.040
that we could all
be proud of.

07:20.040 --> 07:23.620
All I know is, at home,
you call out racism

07:23.620 --> 07:26.880
and tell us
we need to always take a stand,

07:26.880 --> 07:31.170
but I guess it's different
for a strong black man at work.

07:31.170 --> 07:34.120
I'ma go wait in the car,
Boo.

07:37.620 --> 07:40.500
Actually, I'm gonna need
the key fob.

07:47.830 --> 07:50.670
How's my strong black mens?
[ Laughs ]

07:50.670 --> 07:52.290
Why don't you ask him?

07:52.290 --> 07:53.710
[ Refrigerator door opens ]

07:53.710 --> 07:54.960
What's he talking about?

07:54.960 --> 07:56.460
Oh, I made a mistake.

07:56.460 --> 07:58.330
Oh?
He's not ready
for the real world.

07:58.330 --> 08:00.920
Oh, my God. Wait.
Did -- Did he have tree nuts?

08:00.920 --> 08:03.330
He accused me
of being a sellout, Bow.

08:03.330 --> 08:04.670
Oh.
He crossed the line.

08:04.670 --> 08:07.000
Okay.
I always take a stand.

08:07.000 --> 08:08.830
I-I donate
to Black Lives Matter.

08:08.830 --> 08:10.330
I don't shop at H&M.

08:10.330 --> 08:13.330
And I didn't go back
to Chick-fil-A after a week

08:13.330 --> 08:15.210
like some people.

08:15.210 --> 08:16.580
[ Quietly ]
It's really good.

08:16.580 --> 08:17.880
He spent one day
in my office,

08:17.880 --> 08:19.080
and he thinks
he knows everything.

08:19.080 --> 08:21.170
Bow, I fight racism
every day!

08:21.170 --> 08:23.040
I know.
When I first got
to Stevens & Lido,

08:23.040 --> 08:25.170
it was like Boston
in the '70s.

08:25.170 --> 08:28.330
Now because of me,
it's like Boston in the '90s.

08:28.330 --> 08:29.670
[ Normal voice ] Sounds like
he really got to you.

08:29.670 --> 08:31.830
No.
Not at all.

08:31.830 --> 08:33.000
Okay.
But I will tell you this.

08:33.000 --> 08:34.580
Hmm?
He's not coming back
to my office.

08:34.580 --> 08:36.830
As a matter of fact,
I'm removing him

08:36.830 --> 08:41.460
from the family Christmas photo,
so...

08:41.460 --> 08:43.880
Yes, he, uh --
he did get to me.

08:43.880 --> 08:45.920
Aww.
Look, Dre.

08:45.920 --> 08:47.790
If you don't think
he got the full picture,

08:47.790 --> 08:49.880
then why don't you have him
go back to work

08:49.880 --> 08:53.120
so he can see
the final result?

08:53.120 --> 08:55.290
Maybe you're right.
Yeah.

08:55.290 --> 08:57.250
He only got to see me
steering the car,

08:57.250 --> 08:59.120
not drive it
across the finish line.

08:59.120 --> 09:01.380
Yeah, there you go.

09:01.380 --> 09:02.920
And I'ma take
that checkered flag,

09:02.920 --> 09:04.080
and I'm gonna shove it
[bleep]
Okay, okay.
Do you want a grape?

09:04.080 --> 09:05.210
Grape?

09:05.210 --> 09:07.790
♪♪

09:07.790 --> 09:08.920
[ Door opens ]

09:08.920 --> 09:11.380
Aww, buddy.

09:11.380 --> 09:14.040
You're never going to be able
to crack that code.

09:15.040 --> 09:16.460
Come on.

09:16.460 --> 09:18.580
I'll put on "Nemo"
for you.

09:18.580 --> 09:20.460
That'd be great.
Mm-hmm.

09:20.460 --> 09:22.580
If I hadn't cracked it.

09:22.580 --> 09:24.120
Wait, what?

09:24.120 --> 09:25.750
How'd you figure out
the code Dad used?

09:25.750 --> 09:27.080
Found a Post-it
in his nightstand

09:27.080 --> 09:28.790
with the code on it.
Really?!

09:28.790 --> 09:31.250
And I watched "Unfriended"
without parental guidance.

09:31.250 --> 09:32.960
Ha!
You mocked me,

09:32.960 --> 09:35.080
but now who's seen
the scariest movie ever

09:35.080 --> 09:36.420
and will probably have
nightmares?

09:36.420 --> 09:38.290
Okay.
So what's the code?

09:38.290 --> 09:39.460
Uh, nope.

09:39.460 --> 09:41.250
Not happening.

09:41.250 --> 09:44.750
But, Jack, this is
a business opportunity.

09:44.750 --> 09:46.580
Really?
Yeah.

09:46.580 --> 09:48.080
Tell me more.

09:48.080 --> 09:51.330
E-Even if it takes
all night.

09:51.330 --> 09:53.790
Are you afraid
to go to bed?

09:53.790 --> 09:55.920
That movie was
so messed up.

09:55.920 --> 09:57.170
♪♪

09:57.170 --> 09:59.170
Hey, good morning,
everyone.
Good morning.

09:59.170 --> 10:02.120
Was a hot start yesterday
with Hometown Market,

10:02.120 --> 10:04.080
so let's just
jump back in.

10:04.080 --> 10:07.960
How about N.W.A-1 Burger?

10:07.960 --> 10:09.210
[ Chuckling ]

10:09.210 --> 10:10.620
Bullseye, Dad.

10:10.620 --> 10:11.880
Okay, guys.

10:11.880 --> 10:17.500
Uh, I think this rapper thing
is kind of...corny.

10:17.500 --> 10:19.500
Ooh, okay.

10:19.500 --> 10:23.040
All right. Well, we do not want
to come off as out of touch,

10:23.040 --> 10:24.290
so thank you, Dre.

10:24.290 --> 10:26.460
Oh. Okay.

10:26.460 --> 10:28.960
Okay, so Josh and I were
talking earlier in the kitchen

10:28.960 --> 10:31.460
about how a character
or a spokesperson

10:31.460 --> 10:33.710
might appeal
to the urban consumer.

10:33.710 --> 10:35.000
Right, like Joe Camel.

10:35.000 --> 10:36.960
Ooh. Listening.

10:36.960 --> 10:38.620
But it is a restaurant,

10:38.620 --> 10:40.620
so, obviously,
it has to be a woman.

10:40.620 --> 10:41.540
Right.

10:41.540 --> 10:42.540
But not a regular woman.

10:42.540 --> 10:43.540
A fun one.

10:43.540 --> 10:44.670
But no nonsense.

10:44.670 --> 10:47.330
Okay. You mean a woman
that's, uh, independent.

10:47.330 --> 10:49.170
Intelligent.
Charismatic.

10:49.170 --> 10:50.500
Exactly!

10:50.500 --> 10:51.830
Okay.
Sassy.

10:51.830 --> 10:53.330
It's a sassy black woman!

10:53.330 --> 10:54.330
"Heeey!" You know.

10:54.330 --> 10:56.250
Okay, guys.

10:56.250 --> 10:57.540
Trust me.

10:57.540 --> 11:01.080
We do not want a caricature
of a black woman.

11:01.080 --> 11:02.250
No, no, Dre. Look.

11:02.250 --> 11:04.000
What I mean is, like,

11:04.000 --> 11:08.380
the sassy Pine-Sol woman
or, um, sassy Annie, huh?

11:08.380 --> 11:09.830
From the Popeyes chicken
commercials?

11:09.830 --> 11:12.170
Okay, that's exactly
what I'm talking about.

11:12.170 --> 11:14.670
All right?
Those are always the go-to.

11:14.670 --> 11:17.000
Plus those images are
already out there.

11:17.000 --> 11:19.420
Come on, guys. Can't --
Can't we find something fresher

11:19.420 --> 11:20.710
for Hometown Market?

11:20.710 --> 11:23.830
Look, Dre, these spokespeople
are huge successes.

11:23.830 --> 11:25.170
We need something like that,

11:25.170 --> 11:29.290
like a Mama Somebody
or like a Sister Whatever.

11:29.290 --> 11:30.380
Sister...

11:30.380 --> 11:31.460
Auntie! Auntie.

11:31.460 --> 11:32.790
I saw that once
in a movie.

11:32.790 --> 11:35.790
Auntie. That is great.
I love it.

11:35.790 --> 11:37.790
No!
It's -- It's not great.

11:37.790 --> 11:40.290
It's, uh --
It's irresponsible.

11:40.290 --> 11:41.790
Do you think
that's the only way

11:41.790 --> 11:43.460
that black people want
to see themselves?

11:43.460 --> 11:46.540
Huh? Do you think
that's who we are?

11:46.540 --> 11:48.710
Dre, people are gonna
love her.

11:48.710 --> 11:50.580
I don't love her!

11:50.580 --> 11:53.790
And I find it offensive.

11:53.790 --> 11:54.750
All right, Dre.

11:54.750 --> 11:58.120
All right.
I hear you.

11:58.120 --> 11:59.710
Why don't we just take
a few minutes?

11:59.710 --> 12:02.580
We'll regroup,
and we will...

12:02.580 --> 12:04.120
figure out a new course,
okay?

12:04.120 --> 12:07.080
Okay.

12:07.080 --> 12:08.580
Okay.

12:10.460 --> 12:12.330
Yeah.

12:12.330 --> 12:13.620
I'm just gonna call home
real quick,

12:13.620 --> 12:15.420
and then I'll scrub in.

12:18.120 --> 12:20.170
Devante? Devante?

12:20.170 --> 12:21.290
Hey, sweetie.

12:21.290 --> 12:22.250
[ Devante coos ]
Hi.

12:22.250 --> 12:23.170
Wait. Why --

12:23.170 --> 12:24.250
Why do you have
the phone?

12:24.250 --> 12:25.500
Where's --
Where's Grandma?

12:25.500 --> 12:27.250
Are you by yourself,
sweetheart?

12:27.250 --> 12:28.830
Devante?
What's happening?

12:28.830 --> 12:31.580
[ Phone falls ]
Mo-- Oh, okay!
Mom, can you -- oh, my God.

12:31.580 --> 12:33.080
Okay.
Um, I'm coming! Mommy's coming!

12:33.080 --> 12:34.170
Mommy's coming!

12:35.500 --> 12:37.080
Oh, God.
Oh, my God.

12:37.080 --> 12:39.290
Ruby,
where were you?

12:39.290 --> 12:40.580
I had to leave
a surgery.

12:40.580 --> 12:43.830
What -- Why is he
in the baby cage,

12:43.830 --> 12:45.290
and why does he have
a phone?

12:45.290 --> 12:46.830
Oh,
I thought it would be okay

12:46.830 --> 12:48.750
since he had
so much free time...

12:48.750 --> 12:51.460
Wha--
...to explore in the ball pit
at IKEA.

12:51.460 --> 12:52.620
Oh, my God.

12:52.620 --> 12:55.620
In the ball pit?!

12:55.620 --> 12:58.120
They put numbers on the kids
so you don't lose them,

12:58.120 --> 13:01.790
and I even fed him
a Swedish meatball

13:01.790 --> 13:03.460
through the ball-pit net.

13:03.460 --> 13:05.170
[ Chuckles ]
He loved it.

13:05.170 --> 13:09.290
Okay. So you didn't follow
any of my rules?

13:09.290 --> 13:11.170
Rainbow.

13:11.170 --> 13:14.620
All those rules are the reasons
you can't keep a nanny.

13:14.620 --> 13:18.290
Now, they'd complain to me,
and I defended you!

13:18.290 --> 13:19.540
But now I get it.

13:19.540 --> 13:20.620
[ Chuckles ]

13:20.620 --> 13:23.120
Also,
I never defended you.

13:23.120 --> 13:24.290
Yeah, okay.

13:24.290 --> 13:30.960
I -- I tried
for like two whole, long days,

13:30.960 --> 13:34.880
but you cannot be
Devante's nanny.

13:34.880 --> 13:36.670
But I love watching him.

13:36.670 --> 13:38.330
Yes, well, you should have
thought of that

13:38.330 --> 13:41.170
before you gave him a meatball
through a net.

13:41.170 --> 13:42.750
[ Inhales sharply,
sighs ]

13:42.750 --> 13:44.580
Yeah.

13:44.580 --> 13:48.330
It's best
we...part ways.

13:48.330 --> 13:50.500
[ Exhales forcefully ]

13:50.500 --> 13:52.920
Dad,
that was amazing!

13:52.920 --> 13:54.330
Mm-hmm.
The looks on their faces.

13:54.330 --> 13:56.670
You spoke truth
to power!

13:56.670 --> 13:58.250
You know what, son?

13:58.250 --> 13:59.880
I'm glad you were there
to witness it.

13:59.880 --> 14:02.000
Yeah,
my dad is Kaepernick.

14:02.000 --> 14:04.830
Ah, well, you know, son,
I just do what I can.

14:04.830 --> 14:06.500
-Hey, Dre.
-[ Chuckles ] Oh.

14:06.500 --> 14:08.500
Junior.
Ah, listen, we were chatting,

14:08.500 --> 14:11.250
and we actually like
the direction we're headed,

14:11.250 --> 14:12.920
so I decided that we're gonna
keep moving

14:12.920 --> 14:15.290
on the campaign
without you,

14:15.290 --> 14:16.920
so take the rest
of the day,

14:16.920 --> 14:18.040
and I'll see you tomorrow.

14:20.210 --> 14:21.790
At least you don't have
to do it.

14:21.790 --> 14:23.040
That's good news, right?

14:23.040 --> 14:27.210
No, it's not.

14:27.210 --> 14:28.960
They're icing me out,
son.

14:31.120 --> 14:33.210
I am Kaepernick.

14:39.620 --> 14:40.540
I can't believe
they iced me out.

14:40.540 --> 14:41.710
It's just one account,
Dad.

14:41.710 --> 14:45.040
Yeah, that they don't want
my opinion on, son.

14:45.040 --> 14:47.620
You know, when -- when that
happens on projects,

14:47.620 --> 14:51.040
you know, it snowballs
to the next and the next

14:51.040 --> 14:55.120
and then I'll be doing
radio ads for walk-in tubs,

14:55.120 --> 14:56.790
and they're not
the classy ones.

14:56.790 --> 14:59.750
The plastic ones
that you add to existing tubs.

14:59.750 --> 15:01.920
There's got to be something
you can do.

15:04.620 --> 15:06.580
I might have to quit my job,
son.

15:06.580 --> 15:07.580
No.

15:07.580 --> 15:11.080
You know, son,
when...

15:11.080 --> 15:14.920
when you make a stand,
there are consequences.

15:14.920 --> 15:17.120
Sure, black people
are proud

15:17.120 --> 15:19.960
when they see a photo
of John Carlos and Tommie Smith

15:19.960 --> 15:22.250
raising their fists
at the '68 Olympics,

15:22.250 --> 15:26.080
but that protest
got them death threats.

15:26.080 --> 15:30.420
Muhammad Ali -- he stood tall
against Vietnam,

15:30.420 --> 15:33.790
and that got him arrested,
and they took his titles.

15:34.920 --> 15:36.750
I wanted you
to take a stand,

15:36.750 --> 15:40.620
but I didn't think
about the consequences.

15:40.620 --> 15:43.380
This is all my fault.

15:43.380 --> 15:45.290
Kinda.

15:45.290 --> 15:46.620
I'm just joking,
son.

15:46.620 --> 15:48.960
Come on, now.

15:48.960 --> 15:50.830
It's not your fault
at all.

15:52.960 --> 15:55.120
I have to always think
about consequences.

15:55.120 --> 15:56.500
If I take a stand,
does that mean I have

15:56.500 --> 15:58.500
to pull you guys
out of private school

15:58.500 --> 16:00.040
or lose our house?

16:00.040 --> 16:01.500
Damn.

16:01.500 --> 16:06.330
Look, son. What I'm saying
is that when you protest,

16:06.330 --> 16:09.620
it's not something
that comes easy,

16:09.620 --> 16:11.460
and I want you
to appreciate that

16:11.460 --> 16:13.460
the way that I appreciate you
helping me see

16:13.460 --> 16:17.460
that now is the time for me
to do this.

16:17.460 --> 16:21.080
So thank you, son.

16:21.080 --> 16:24.830
I'm actually prouder of you now
than I was 20 minutes ago.

16:24.830 --> 16:26.000
[ Hits desk ]

16:26.000 --> 16:28.040
Now.

16:28.040 --> 16:32.000
Before we get out of here,
let's, uh --

16:32.000 --> 16:34.170
let's put some shrimp
in the vents.

16:34.170 --> 16:39.380
♪♪

16:39.380 --> 16:41.170
Ruby: Hey.
I'll see you later.

16:41.170 --> 16:44.250
I'm going to drink margaritas
at the TGI Fridays

16:44.250 --> 16:47.500
with everyone else
who got fired today.

16:47.500 --> 16:49.540
Well, that sounds fun.

16:49.540 --> 16:51.250
Bye.

16:51.250 --> 16:53.040
B-- Hey, what you got
on his head?

16:53.040 --> 16:54.580
Oh, no, no, no, no, no.
No.

16:54.580 --> 16:58.500
We are re-enacting
the Destiny's Child
"Survivor" video.

16:58.500 --> 17:00.580
Hey, Beyoncé!
Boom, boom.

17:00.580 --> 17:02.290
I always thought of him
as a Kelly.

17:02.290 --> 17:03.540
Aww, really?
Hey, Boo. That's cute.

17:03.540 --> 17:04.580
No. No, no, no.

17:04.580 --> 17:06.210
Oh. Oh, God.

17:06.210 --> 17:08.210
Oh, my goodness.

17:08.210 --> 17:09.460
What happened?

17:09.460 --> 17:12.750
[ Sighs ]

17:12.750 --> 17:16.250
He -- He fell
while I was watching him.

17:16.250 --> 17:19.380
Did that floor try to take
a bite out of that baby?
It wasn't bad.

17:19.380 --> 17:21.380
[ Stomps feet ]
Bad floor.
Yeah.

17:21.380 --> 17:22.540
[ Stomps feet ]
Bad floor.
[ Devante laughs ]

17:22.540 --> 17:24.960
[ Laughing ]
Yeah, I see that.

17:24.960 --> 17:28.210
When he gets hurt,
we pretend to get revenge,

17:28.210 --> 17:29.460
and that makes him laugh.

17:29.460 --> 17:31.750
Yeah, he's okay.
[ Devante laughs ]

17:31.750 --> 17:33.420
You're so good with him,
Ruby.

17:33.420 --> 17:36.420
Yeah, well, Rainbow,
I loved watching him.

17:36.420 --> 17:38.380
While it lasted.

17:38.380 --> 17:40.880
I know I'm overprotective,
Ruby.

17:40.880 --> 17:42.460
Yeah.

17:42.460 --> 17:45.420
But I can't give 100%
at my job

17:45.420 --> 17:48.790
if I'm busy worrying about
who's taking care of Devante.

17:48.790 --> 17:50.580
[ Sighs ]

17:50.580 --> 17:52.080
Yeah, he's gonna be
all right.

17:52.080 --> 17:53.790
He's fine.
Yeah.

17:53.790 --> 17:54.960
Ruby.

17:54.960 --> 17:56.170
Yeah?

17:56.170 --> 17:59.920
Do you want to be
Devante's nanny again?

17:59.920 --> 18:01.330
Hmm.

18:01.330 --> 18:03.580
Unbelievable.

18:03.580 --> 18:05.420
I'd be honored.

18:05.420 --> 18:06.460
Come here.

18:06.460 --> 18:07.460
Thank you, Ruby.

18:07.460 --> 18:08.460
[ Chuckles ]
Thank you so much.

18:08.460 --> 18:10.750
Aww.

18:10.750 --> 18:13.170
Now I'm gonna need
four weeks off at Christmas.

18:13.170 --> 18:15.750
[ Sighs ]

18:15.750 --> 18:17.460
You know where I go.

18:17.460 --> 18:19.120
[ Hums ]

18:19.120 --> 18:20.080
♪♪

18:20.080 --> 18:21.080
Ooh, Splenda.
All right,

18:21.080 --> 18:22.580
and I know you think
I'm above this,

18:22.580 --> 18:24.920
but next, we gonna fill
this backpack with staplers.

18:24.920 --> 18:26.000
Come on.
Put it in there.

18:26.000 --> 18:27.620
-Dre! Oh!
-Put the rest in your pocket.

18:27.620 --> 18:29.120
There you are, hey.

18:29.120 --> 18:31.040
Listen.
Um, I was thinking,

18:31.040 --> 18:34.290
um, how would you like
a much better parking spot

18:34.290 --> 18:36.960
or, um, access
to our Laker box seats

18:36.960 --> 18:38.460
when the Warriors
are in town

18:38.460 --> 18:41.120
or, um,
a shiny new necklace?

18:41.120 --> 18:43.460
What did you do?

18:43.460 --> 18:46.460
Well, we -- we might have jumped
the gun with Hometown Market.

18:46.460 --> 18:48.120
We have a great pitch
for you.

18:48.120 --> 18:50.710
So imagine I'm an urban mother,
and this is my child.

18:50.710 --> 18:52.120
I'm hungry, yo.

18:52.120 --> 18:53.790
Oh,
should we get take-out?

18:53.790 --> 18:55.170
Should we get fast food?

18:55.170 --> 18:57.790
Or should we go
to a competing,

18:57.790 --> 19:01.210
mid-range,
casual restaurant?

19:01.210 --> 19:03.290
[ As Auntie No No ]
No, no, baby.

19:03.290 --> 19:06.790
Auntie No No gonna give you
a plate from Hometown Market.

19:06.790 --> 19:09.500
Mmm, mmm, mmm, child.

19:13.710 --> 19:15.000
Well, that can't be good.

19:15.000 --> 19:19.040
So, uh, we really need you
back in the room, Dre.

19:19.040 --> 19:20.500
-Oh.
-Yeah.

19:20.500 --> 19:23.250
Okay, because I have
some thoughts.

19:23.250 --> 19:26.170
I can't be my best
when I'm wasting my energy

19:26.170 --> 19:28.920
saving you guys
from yourselves.

19:28.920 --> 19:31.750
Okay? You're gonna need
to step up and do better.

19:31.750 --> 19:33.170
Oh, my God.

19:33.170 --> 19:34.750
I thought you were gonna
ask for more money.

19:34.750 --> 19:36.830
Yeah, no,
we can do better.

19:36.830 --> 19:40.000
A-At least, we'll try.

19:40.000 --> 19:42.330
How does that sound
to you, son?

19:42.330 --> 19:44.380
Sounds like a start.

19:44.380 --> 19:45.420
Thank you, Dre.

19:45.420 --> 19:46.580
Uh-huh.

19:48.420 --> 19:49.710
Dre.
Charlie?

19:49.710 --> 19:51.460
Where you been?

19:51.460 --> 19:53.790
They asked me what I thought
about the Auntie No No campaign,

19:53.790 --> 19:55.120
so I've been hiding.

19:55.120 --> 19:56.460
I can't get involved
in this.

19:56.460 --> 19:58.620
I cannot have Black Twitter
after me again.

19:58.620 --> 20:00.080
Don't worry, Charlie.

20:00.080 --> 20:02.120
It's already been
taken care of.

20:02.120 --> 20:04.380
My dad handled
his business.
Mm-hmm.

20:04.380 --> 20:05.960
[ Imitates slap ]
Hey.

20:05.960 --> 20:09.040
Dre's got a friend,
college boy.

20:09.040 --> 20:12.710
Did you just make
your own slap sound?

20:12.710 --> 20:13.790
No.

20:13.790 --> 20:15.250
You definitely did.

20:15.250 --> 20:16.420
No, that was --
that's what --

20:16.420 --> 20:18.380
that's what my slaps
sound like.

20:23.040 --> 20:24.750
Thank you for joining us
at Johnson Theaters,

20:24.750 --> 20:26.750
the premiere spot
for R-rated films.

20:26.750 --> 20:29.620
So, tonight,
we are screening "It."

20:29.620 --> 20:30.670
[ Murmurs of approval ]

20:30.670 --> 20:31.920
My brother will now open
the door

20:31.920 --> 20:33.960
to a world
of shocking violence,

20:33.960 --> 20:35.920
inappropriate language,
and adult themes.

20:35.920 --> 20:38.460
[ Murmurs of approval ]
Jack, the code?

20:40.080 --> 20:42.420
[ Beep ]

20:42.420 --> 20:43.330
[ Chuckles nervously ]

20:43.330 --> 20:44.290
[ Beep ]

20:44.290 --> 20:45.790
What's the hold-up?

20:45.790 --> 20:46.790
I threw away
the Post-it,

20:46.790 --> 20:48.500
and now I can't remember
the numbers.

20:48.500 --> 20:49.750
Um...

20:49.750 --> 20:51.750
0-0-0-1.
[ Beep ]

20:51.750 --> 20:54.000
Dang it!
Um...

20:54.000 --> 20:57.750
I was promised shocking violence
and boobs and/or butts!

20:57.750 --> 20:58.920
[ Murmurs of agreement ]

20:58.920 --> 21:01.120
I don't know what kind of man
I am yet.

21:01.120 --> 21:02.460
I want a refund.

21:02.460 --> 21:03.960
-Yeah.
-Refund!

21:03.960 --> 21:05.080
[ All chanting "Refund" ]

21:05.080 --> 21:07.620
Hey, guys.
No need to get upset.

21:07.620 --> 21:09.790
[ Chuckles ] We can still
be exposed to adult themes,

21:09.790 --> 21:11.080
right?

21:11.080 --> 21:12.460
Um, okay, so here's
what happened

21:12.460 --> 21:14.960
on an episode of "Ballers"
that, um, I saw by accident.

21:14.960 --> 21:17.170
Shh-shh.
So, um, okay,

21:17.170 --> 21:21.000
the guys are at a rooftop bar,
and it is going off.
